In [21]:
clusters=range(2,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_cluster)
    prediction=model.predict(df_cluster)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_cluster, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_cluster.shape[0])
In [22]:
# Plot a visual and find elbow point
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within Sum Square')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

def standarization(df_new,df_orginal):
    for i in df_new.columns:
        if(df[i].max()>=df_new[i].max() and df[i].min()<=df_new[i].min() ):
            df_new[i] = (df_new[i] - df[i].mean())/df[i].std(ddof=0)
        else:
            print("We got a new max/min value so revise the model")

   macro avg       0.89      0.88      0.88       846
weighted avg       0.89      0.89      0.89       846

Looks like by drop reducing dimensionality by 6, the accuracy has been decreased. This is insample (on training data) and hence a drop in accuracy is expected. Still seems easy to justify the dropping of variables. An out of sample (on test data), with the 6 independent variables is likely to do better since that would be less of an over-fit.

Data Understanding & Cleaning¶

In [59]:
#Explain pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA

Pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA :-

  1. There must be linearity in the data set, i.e. the variables combine in a linear manner to form the dataset.
  2. The variables exhibit relationships among themselves.
  3. PCA assumes that the principal component with high variance must be paid attention and the PCs with lower variance are disregarded as noise
In [60]:
#Explain advantages and limitations of PCA

Advantages -

  1. Removes Correlated Features
  2. Improves Algorithm Performance
  3. Reduces Overfitting
  4. Improves Visualization

Disadvantages -

  1. Independent variables become less interpretable
  2. Data standardization is must before PCA
